Food debt to European inflation
The main reason for the increase in inflation in the eurozone was the rapid rise in food prices.
In the 13 eurozone countries, prices were higher than expected in November - after 2.6 percent in October, an annual inflation rate of 3.1 percent was recorded, as reported by the EU Statistical Office in Luxembourg.
Official forecasts were based on only 3 percent, reported Bloomberg.
The European Central Bank (ECB) has not lowered the leitzens in contrast to the American, British, and Canadian banks. Its discretion would favour the rise in raw material prices and the slight decline in unemployment, which would favour the emergence of a spiral of inflation.
The ECB seeks to keep the inflation rate below two percent, or at least close to the two percent mark.
According to an analyst, the ECB is located in the Zwickmühle: inflation has to be "absorbed" in order to exclude subsequent needs for action.
At 3.3 per cent, the inflation rate in November in Germany reached a twelve-year record high; in Spain the rate climbed from 3.6 to 4.1 per cent.
The increase in inflation in the euro area was responsible for increasing food and energy prices.
The MATIF wheat quotations rose by 88 percent, and the price for soybeans has also reached a record high since 1973.
Food oil and dairy products were also very expensive in 2007.
The world market price for crude oil rose by 52 percent this year - last month the price per barrel of black gold reached almost 100 US dollars.
According to the ECB, inflation will rise from 2.1 to 2.5 percent in 2008, but in 2009 it is estimated that it will decrease to 1.9 percent.
For the next 3-4 months, analysts assume a 3-percent inflation rate, but the annual average rate is 2.1 percent.
For 2008, experts estimate that the ECB will reduce interest rates twice.
