Hungary’s 6 per cent
Environment Minister Gábor Fodor, on behalf of Hungary, supports the EU's efforts to maintain its pioneering role in global climate protection measures and to achieve a new international agreement by 2009.
The Minister said that the EU would reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 20% by 2020 (as measured by the 1990 values), regardless of whether the "after 2012 agreement" was successful, or not. The Union would even be willing to commit itself to a 30% reduction, provided other major industrial countries in the world, or developing countries, are also willing to comply with their obligations by force and responsibility.
Gábor Fodor stressed that the target of the countries that had joined the Kyoto Protocol in 1997 was a reduction of only 5.2 percent, whereas the EU had already committed itself to a reduction of 8% with its 15 Member States at that time.
The target for Hungary is to reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 6% compared to 1985-87 - a requirement that the country will fully meet, as can be seen in the press release of the Ministry of the Environment.
The commitment is high on Bali - after all, the long-term international climate policy agreement must be completed within two years, otherwise it would certainly come into force only after 2012. In this case, the reduction projects set out in the Kyoto Protocol would not follow a new international emission reduction system, which also highlighted the importance of the IPCC, the International Nobel Peace Prize (IPCC), the UN Scientific Committee on Climate Change in its recent report.
This would delay emission reduction, and the increase in Earth's average temperature by more than 2°C would be inevitable, which, according to scientists, would result in extremely serious and irreparable consequences.
