Holidays are not everywhere holidays
Holidays in Hungary are precisely regulated by law, so that the practice of redeploying the working days around the holidays has now established itself, but the coming year gives us fewer days.
In the EU and in America, too, we see something different under "Federal Day".
The Hungarian legal system distinguishes between public holidays and days free of work.
Unemployed days are usually ecclesial holidays, or are associated with significant historical events.
For example, we also celebrate New Year: both the last day of the old, and the first day of the new year are days without work - the latter alone so that the New Year celebrations can rest.
All year long we have a total of fourteen holidays.
The public holidays are the 15th of March, which commemorates the revolution of 1848, and the 23rd of October, the Memorial of the Revolution of 1956.
On August 20th, the founding of the state, on May 1st, will be celebrated the work, on November 1st and 2nd, we will remember our dead.
In addition, there are every two holidays on Easter, Pentecost, and Christmas.
Since our state, national or religious holidays rarely fall on a weekend, the practice of "working day shifting" has proven itself in cases where we would only work one day before or after the holiday.
The price of the extended weekends, however, is that we have to work very well on the Saturdays before that, or go to school.
When this day, which falls before or after the holiday, is finally to be worked out, the Minister of Labour has been in a separate regulation for many years.
The legislation applies equally to all employers, public employees and civil servants.
Only companies and facilities in which the operation is continued without interruption, i.e. on public holidays, are excluded.
Today, the working order is only confused by the holiday at the end of the year: from 24 December, life in this country will remain formal, as most will take time compensation for the days between Christmas and New Year, or the special holiday for it.
In the next year there will be more holidays in the middle of the week, or at the end of the week, so that there will be fewer redundancies in working days than this year.
The calendar is first set up around the day of work, so that people can stay at home for four days.
Saturday, April 26th will be a working day so that Friday, May 2nd can be a day of rest.
The second re-disposal will be on the 23rd of October: Saturday, 18th of October you will have to finish Friday, 24th of October.
The end of the year, however, will remain unreserved in the sign of the holidays, after everything will lie and stand from December 24, even if New Year's Eve falls on a Wednesday.
