After more than 60 years of confidential treatment, the Nazi archives of Bad Arolsen, which document the fates of 17.5 million victims of the Hitler regime, are now freely accessible.
The 47 million documents of the archive, which are housed at a total length of 27 km in Bad Arolsen, could not be seen until now, except with a humanitarian intention, that is to say, individually and on behalf of a former victim or his family.
In May 2006, the eleven States entrusted with their administration, including Germany, France, Israel and the United States, agreed to make them available to researchers and historians.
After the ratification process of this Decision has been completed, the opening has been valid since yesterday.
Heckle information
Access by historians to Bad Arolsen will allow research to be carried out, especially on the deportations of prisoners, the inmates of the concentration camps and the health status of forced labour, explains Reto Masters, the director of this archive, who are managed by the International Committee of the Red Cross (CICR).
Until recently, several states, including Germany, were opposed to making these name-related documents available to the public due to the delicate nature of certain information.
Like, for example, the alleged homosexuality or the mental disability of some deportation victims.
The prisoners of the concentration camps or the warrants issued by the Gestapo had been collected after the war for a practical reason: to find civilians who had been deported or subjected to forced labour, and possibly to provide them with evidence of their arrest in order to pave the way for their compensation.
Even today in Bad Arolsen, more than 300 permanent employees are working on tens of thousands of personal requests.
However, part of the scientific community shows only a limited interest in access to Bad Arolsen.
It is not possible to expect anything fundamentally new in these documents, Pr. Wolfgang Benz, Head of the Research Center for Anti-Semitism of the Technical University of Berlin, explained in 2006.
