These aren't Warhol's boxes.
Who connects the terms Sweden and wooden chests is thinking of Ikea, but not of Andy Warhol.
Isn't it?
Currently in Sweden fabricated wooden boxes cast dark shadows on Warhol's work directory.
Most of the well-listed Brillo boxes from "Typ Stockholm" listed there are fakes.
After the Swedish newspaper "Expressen" a few months ago has aroused doubts about the authenticity of Andy Warhol's Brillo boxes of the year 1968, internal research at the Moderna Museet in Stockholm is now coming to a sobering conclusion: the six "Brillo boxes", which the former museum director Pontus Hultén has made to the Moderna Museet in 1995, are copies - and most of the approximately one hundred more Brillo boxes of "Type Stockholm", which are in circulation on the international art market.
The prehistory is shattered, a confusing chain of artistic and curatorial productions.
In 1964 Warhol created his first "Brillo-Boxes", painted wooden boxes based on the red-blue-white design of the cardboard box of the soap powder "Brillo".
An exhibition of his works at the Moderna Museet in 1968, with Warhol's approval, produced hundreds of Brillo boxes from cardboard: These were not from Warhol for cost reasons, but were delivered directly from the Brillo cardboard factory.
It was not works of art, but their role models, just exhibits.
At the same time, in 1968, Warhol probably granted permission to produce a few Brillo wood caskets in Sweden, which were not exhibited in the Moderna Museet.
Zeitzeugen now speaks of about fifteen crates, which at that time have rightly been included in the art and auction history as authorised original Andy-Warhol-Brillo-Boxes called "Type Stockholm".
Some of them have achieved more than 100 000 dollars at auctions.
The problem is that the legendary museum director Pontus Hultén later falsely claimed that it had been produced and exhibited around a hundred wooden boxes in Sweden in 1968, which Warhol had then left him.
In fact, Hultén's 105 crates were not produced until 1990 in Malmö for an exhibition in St. Petersburg.
At that time, Warhol had been dead for three years.
Lars Byström, Chief Conservator at Moderna Museet, has also examined three Swedish private holdings in addition to the six museum-owned Brillo boxes, two of which were manufactured in Stockholm in 1968: their press strips were first ground and shredded, and then white oil paint was applied with a brush.
The structure of the 1990 copies, on the other hand, reveals that the colour was applied directly to the press panel without any foundation, not to oil, but to acrylic paint.
"These boxes were not authorized by the artist and should be removed from the official list of Andy Warhol's Brillo-Boxes," said the director of Moderna Museet, Lars Nittve: "If the 'Andy Warhol Art Authentication Board' in New York does not come to a different conclusion, the Moderna Museet will classify the six boxes in its collection as copies/exhibition material."
As early as July, the Authentication Board announced to investigate the "serious allegations" raised in the case of soap powder boxes.
But since then, there has been unspeakable silence.
